day 11 
- to work on maven, multiple jar file is required, and each version of jar depends on the previouly exported jar file 
- before maven, jar file was supposed to be carried, like portable 
- and in maven, the project structure is created, and the required jar file is downloaded automatically. 
- maven sets the environment directly 
- maven is automatic project build tool, and provide a way to run and deploy the application 
- in hiberate, 
    - less manual code 
    - no sql knowledge is required   
    - loosely coupled with database
   - uses object oriented query
- in springboot, almost no manual code 
- jdbc, 
    - a lot of manual code
    - sql knowledge is needed
    - tightly coupled with database 
      - uses primitive oriented query

- jpa v hibernate

- jpa is set of standard or specification 
	- it is the interface
- hiberanate is one of the implementation of jpa 
- hiberanate is orm (object relational mapping) framework 
- taking example of ems
- orm
	- object — the employee object — eid, ename, esalary, dno
	- relational — the database 
	- model — the bean class 
- first from the hiberanate code the request will go to the orm 
- and the orm based on the database, it will generate the correct sql query 
- and send back the query
- orm has two config files — hibernate.cfg.xml ( has database connection information/ establishing connection) , hiberanate.hbm.xml ( mapping between table and the model class) 
- till jsp it is bean class, in hiberate is called model class
- hql — hibernate query lang. — object oriented — query along wiht the bean/model/entity class 

- new —> maven project —> tick create simple project 
- the congif of a maven project 
	- group id — is the base package 
	- artifact id — project name 
	-packaging - jar( java archieve)

- src/main/java — core java file 
- src/main/resources — resource files, stores hibernate.cfg.xml and hiberanate.hbm.xml
- src/main/test — contains testing code
- when we work on framework, we need dependences, which maven gets automatically — so you need to tell me what depeneces are needed 
- pom.xml is where we gonna tell what dependences we need 
- maven is downloading dependences for maven dependency repository 
- the jar file is being downloaded in the m2 (maven local repository ) folder
- it is downloading in m2 because, we dont need to download again, and just use this 
- each transaction needs a  seperate session, and hence we need a session factory

day 12 
- in all annotations, entity and id are mandotory
- if there is no table annotation, then it will create a new table with the name of entity i.e. the name of the class 
- the one-to-one or many-to-many is mapping or hibernate association 
- whenever we do mapping, the orm will create the required tables on its own
class Employee{
private int eid;
private String ename;
private double salary;
private idCard = new IdCard( );  // HAS-A relationship 
}
class IdCard( ){
}

- when two classes can exist individually/inpendently, but to make a proper application, we need both of them 
- there are two types of entity— weak and strong 
- one object can have multiple depencd objects 
- tightly coupled system
- object injection
	- dependent object is created outside the application, and when ever needed it will be injected 
	- ioc — inversion of control — creating the dependent object outside the application, when the application starts — the objects will be injected whenever the object is needed 
- ioc need to be told that these are dependent in three ways — xml based config — java code based config — annotation based config 
- ioc container is a global memory in framework
- types of dependency injection 
	- constructor injection — dependences are provided thru constructor 
	- field injection — injected directly into fields 
	- setter injection — provided thru setter method
- application context is the global memory for the entire application — where all the common data is stored — where the ioc stores the objects — and internally it is servlet context — ioc container
- everything we created till now are tightly coupled systems 